<HEADLINE>
<P>
COST OF WAR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In The Times' special section (The Line in the Sand, Nov. 25) concerning the 
Mideast, (Desert Shield commander) Gen. H. Norman Schwarzkopf is quoted as 
saying, "We ought to think a little bit about what the cost is going to be. Not 
only to us, but to the enemy, too." 
</P>
<P>
Cost to the enemy? What does he think the situation is, a swap meet? Is he in 
the military or in the Peace Corps? I wonder what Gens. Eisenhower, MacArthur 
or Grant would have to say about that? 
</P>
<P>
If Schwarzkopf wants to cut costs on both sides, then he should challenge 
Saddam Hussein to a duel and hope that the best man wins. Or is he just another 
(Civil War Gen. George) McClellan? 
</P>
<P>
PAUL C. DILLMAN, Buena Park 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Drawing, Gen. H. Norman Schwarzkopf / TAYLOR JONES, 1990 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
