<P>
PASADENA UNVEILS NEW HUNTINGTON HOSPITAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARY LOU LOPER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Pasadena opened its big Christmas present -- the new Huntington Hospital -- 
early. On Friday night, lights outlined the Mediterranean edges of the 
$75-million three-story replacement structure at 100 W. California Blvd. 
One-thousand (at $200 a ticket) dined and danced to Wayne Foster for a "Pre-Op" 
party and first views of the elegant structure. Another 3,000 Huntington 
Hospital staff and their relatives toured Saturday and 300 more partied at the 
"Operation Party" Saturday night. Sunday afternoon the public swarmed in for 
the "Post-Op" party, a community open house. 
</P>
<P>
"Yes, lots of comparisons to the Ritz Carlton," said hospital president Dr. 
Allen Mathies, greeting guests with his wife, Weta. 
</P>
<P>
The Friday night crowd meandered through admittance offices, and oohed and 
aahed over the gift shop, the newborn nurseries, 13 operating suites and the 
emergency department (including the San Gabriel Valley's only trauma center). 
</P>
<P>
The old core hospital building was erected in 1921. This evening was a goodby 
to grunginess. And hello to fresh paint and partying. In the huge white tent on 
the hospital parking lot, party co-chairs Katie Tuerk and Weta Mathies directed 
Cuisine Cuisine from Newport Beach to serve an antipasto salad, hot chicken and 
a fudge dessert. Ivy topiaries in the shapes of wreaths and Christmas trees 
dotted tables. 
</P>
<P>
Pride was showing. Dinner co-chairs William K. Doyle and Dr. James P. Blitz 
said thank-yous, hosting tables with their wives, Cheryl Doyle and Pam Blitz. 
Doctors were in abundance: Popular Dr. Millard McLain, now retired, got more 
hugs than a teddy bear. There were Dr. Morgans galore -- Dr. George Morgan and 
his son, Dr. Edward Morgan, and daughter-in-law, Dr. Karen Morgan, as well as 
Dr. Stan Morgan, not related. Dr. Bill Corey was on call; his wife carried his 
cellular phone. 
</P>
<P>
Glitter was rampant. Shining in the masses of beads, bangles and diamonds were 
Pasadena-area leaders Verne (Huntington board chairman) and Sarah Orr, Stan and 
Marcia Hayden, Jane and Kris Popovich, Joan and Dean Schneider, Lorna and Chuck 
Reed, Dr. Bob and Jan Tranquada, Cornelius and Marjorie Pings, Patty and Davis 
Pillsbury, Bob and Louisa Miller, Dr. Bill and Susie Lattin, Dr. Mary Lee and 
Shelby Coffey III, Betsy and Frank Ulf, George and Chris Benter, Bill and 
Eileen Zimmerman, Henry and Nancy DeNero, Spike and Debby Booth, Bruce and 
Susan Seidel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Marking Huntington Hospital opening are, from left, Verne Orr, Weta 
Mathies, William K. Doyle, Katie Tuerk, Allen Mathies. ROBERT DURELL / Los 
Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
