<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWS ROUNDUP: THOUSAND OAKS; 
</P>
<P>
NETS MAY KEEP GOLF BALLS OFF FREEWAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PSYCHE PASCUAL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A plan to protect motorists on the Ventura Freeway from flying balls near a 
municipal golf course will be introduced at the Thousand Oaks City Council 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
The City Council will consider paying $70,000 to install 1,500 feet of 
protective nylon nets around the Los Robles Golf Course on Moorpark Road. 
</P>
<P>
Finance Director Robert S. Biery said netting up to 50-feet high may be needed 
where the risk to cars from wayward balls is greatest. 
</P>
<P>
The nets may reduce the number of claims filed by motorists whose vehicles have 
been damaged. 
</P>
<P>
Since 1988, 57 claims have been filed against the city by drivers whose cars 
and windows were smashed by golf balls. The city paid $14,870 to settle the 
claims, according to the city attorney's office. 
</P>
<P>
Officials are concerned that increases in freeway traffic and golfers using the 
course could mean an increase in legal claims. PSYCHE PASCUAL 
</P>
</TEXT>
